{
  "title": "2hollis: Pop Music Made From Internet Feeling",
  "category": "music",
  "author": "Allastair Voss",
  "date": "2026-04-22",
  "image": "/assets/images/artists/2hollis.jpg",
  "body": "[spotify:artist/72NhFAGG5Pt91VbheJeEPG]\n\n[img:/assets/images/artists/2hollis-internet-pop-star.jpg]\n\nThere is a generation of artists who grew up online in a way that actually changed how they make music, not just how they market it. 2hollis is one of them.\n\nThe Chicago-born singer and producer makes pop music that sounds like it was assembled from a particular kind of internet memory: the emotional texture of early 2010s online spaces, the melancholy of digital connection and disconnection, the way certain sounds feel simultaneously nostalgic and very now. It's a specific feeling that most people who were online during a certain period recognize immediately, and 2hollis has figured out how to make it into songs.\n\n\"Finesse\" and \"Body\" introduced him to a wider audience, and both show the core appeal: melodic writing that's direct without being simplistic, production that sits in a genuinely unusual sonic register somewhere between hyperpop textures and classic R&B structure, and an emotional register that doesn't perform vulnerability so much as just inhabit it naturally.\n\n## Where He Comes From\n\nHollis Parker Frazier-Herndon was born in 2004 into a household that treated music as a serious matter. His father is John Herndon, drummer for the Chicago post-rock band Tortoise. His mother is Kathryn Frazier, the founder of PR firm Biz 3 and co-founder of the influential electronic music label Owsla. Growing up in that environment didn't make him a replica of either parent's sensibility. It gave him something more useful: an instinct for what is real in music and what is performance.\n\nHe started producing in high school under the alias Drippysoup before transitioning to 2hollis in 2020. The early material showed someone working through a wide range of influences at speed: EDM, trap, cloud rap, elements of glitchcore and witch house appearing and receding in rapid succession. What stabilized across the experimentation was a consistent emotional temperature, songs that felt like they were made in private for a listener the artist understood deeply.\n\n## The Albums\n\nWhite Tiger arrived in 2022, followed by 2 in 2023, and then Boy in June 2024. The third album is where the synthesis became complete. Boy is an electropop and electroclash record built on unpredictable sound design: compositions that mutate mid-track, production choices that refuse to settle into comfort, and underneath all of it, songwriting that is genuinely moving. His 2023 track \"Poster Boy\" landed on the EA Sports FC 24 soundtrack, reaching listeners who had never searched for him specifically and staying with them anyway. That kind of discovery moment is what happens when the work is strong enough to move without being pushed.\n\nThe singles \"crush\" and \"jeans\" from the Boy campaign demonstrated a melodic instinct that operates cleanly across different production contexts. He is not dependent on a particular sonic palette to communicate. The feeling is the constant, not the texture around it.\n\n## Built Different\n\nWhat's interesting about 2hollis's catalog is the consistency of emotional temperature. The songs aren't all the same, but they share a kind of ambient warmth, an enveloping quality that makes them feel comfortable in a way that's hard to explain but easy to recognize. This is a production skill as much as a songwriting one.\n\nHe has toured extensively, selling out dates across North America and Europe with the kind of audience density that doesn't come from streaming numbers alone. He opened for Ken Carson in markets where he had to earn the room before he had it. He earned the rooms. The live experience confirms something the recordings suggest: this is an artist whose relationship to his audience is genuine, not managed.\n\nWith Hallwood Media management and Wasserman booking, the infrastructure is in place for broader reach. The question isn't whether the talent is there. It clearly is. The question of how an artist whose work is this specifically textured translates to larger rooms has a clear answer based on current trajectory: carefully, and very well.\n\n## Why He Matters\n\nThe internet pop category is crowded with artists who have absorbed the aesthetics of online culture without absorbing its actual emotional logic. 2hollis is different because the online origin of his sensibility is not decorative. It shapes the way he builds tension in a track, the way he writes a hook that hits on the third listen rather than the first, the way his production choices reference a shared experience of digital adolescence without explaining that reference or making it the point.\n\nThe music earns its nostalgia. It doesn't trade on it.\n\n\n## The Catalog So Far\n\nThe three projects that establish 2hollis as a genuine force rather than a viral moment are *White Tiger* (2022), *2* (2023), and *Boy* (2024). Each one extends the palette without abandoning the core: that specific warmth, that production that sits at the boundary between genres without falling into any of them. *Boy* in particular marked a turn toward more direct emotional statement, less reliant on the textural effects that defined the earlier work and more willing to let a lyric carry weight on its own. This is either maturity or confidence or both.\n\nThe placement of \"Poster Boy\" on the EA Sports FC 24 soundtrack was the kind of licensing that introduces an artist to an audience of millions without feeling like a compromise. The track fit the context without being made for it, which is the best a sync placement can be. The result was new listeners who then went back to the catalog rather than waiting for the next single, which is exactly what a sync is supposed to produce when the artist is genuinely good.\n\nThe Hallwood Media and Wasserman partnerships give the infrastructure necessary for the work to reach more people. The management understands what the music is and hasn't pushed it toward a more legible commercial identity. That restraint, paired with growing buzz through touring with artists like Ken Carson, suggests the development arc is proceeding at the right pace. The internet-native pop star model 2hollis represents is still being written. He is writing it.\n\nThe sound is his. The audience is real. The catalog already justifies attention.\n[download:/assets/images/artists/2hollis-internet-pop-star-social-9x16.jpg|Download Social Card]",
  "description": "There is a generation of artists who grew up online in a way that actually changed how they make music, not just how they market it. 2hollis is one of them.",
  "image_alt": "2hollis: Pop Music Made From Internet Feeling"
}
