{
  "title": "Alewya's ZERO Arrives as a Debut Album Worth Every Year of the Wait",
  "category": "music",
  "author": "Allastair Voss",
  "date": "2026-05-20",
  "image": "/assets/images/artists/alewya-zero.jpg",
  "image_position": "center 20%",
  "instagram": "@alewya11",
  "body": "[youtube:_Ejt8HVyQ2w]\n\nAlewya Demmisse has been building toward her debut album for years with the quiet accumulation of an artist who knows exactly what she is making and refuses to release it before it is ready. Born in Saudi Arabia to an Egyptian father and an Ethiopian mother, raised in Sudan before her family relocated to the UK as refugees when she was five, and then grown up in West London, she carries a biographical complexity that her music does not explain or dramatize but simply contains and makes useful. ZERO, announced for June 26, 2026 on Because London Records, is the record she has been signaling since her first singles appeared in 2020. The lead material she has shared in the months before its release suggests an album that earns its title in full.\n\n## The Arrival of Selah\n\n[img:/assets/images/artists/alewya-zero-detail.jpg]\n\nSelah, released in April 2026, was the clearest statement yet of where the album was headed. Directed by Iggy London with creative direction by Lee Trigg, the video places Alewya at the center of a London party coming alive with dancers, color and collective release. The song is built on something that feels simultaneously ancient and immediate: a rhythmic foundation drawing on East African musical heritage, a vocal delivery that moves between restraint and full abandon, and a production sensibility that refuses to anchor itself to any single genre. Alewya has spoken about Selah as a track about communal surrender, about the permission that music creates for collective feeling in a room full of people who have arrived at the same place by different routes. The video makes that permission visible. The choreography is loose and joyful rather than precise, which is itself a statement about what the music is for. It is one of the most fully realized visual statements of her career to date, and among the best pieces of music released in 2026 so far.\n\n## Night Drive and the Return\n\n[img:/assets/images/artists/alewya-zero-detail2.jpg]\n\nBefore Selah, there was Night Drive, released in November 2025 as the first new music after nearly three years away, featuring vocalist and performer Dagmawit Ameha. The single announced a shift in Alewya's artistic direction without abandoning anything that made her first work distinctive. Night Drive is propulsive and atmospheric: a late night anthem built on layered textures designed for movement and sustained attention. The collaboration with Dagmawit Ameha, an Ethiopian musician whose own work explores the intersection of tradition and contemporary electronic sound, reflects something central to Alewya's creative practice. She works with voices and bodies that carry specific cultural weight, and she asks them to carry that weight in new and unexpected configurations. The result is music that belongs to several traditions without being reducible to any of them.\n\n## The Architecture of ZERO\n\n[img:/assets/images/artists/alewya-zero-detail3.jpg]\n\nThe fifteen songs announced for ZERO represent the most ambitious statement of Alewya's career. The singles released in advance suggest a record that holds together emotionally and sonically rather than as a loose collection of separate tracks. Production across both Selah and Night Drive is handled by longtime collaborator Busy Twist, whose approach gives the material a consistent internal logic while leaving room for each track to breathe and move individually. Alewya produced both tracks herself as well, which is consistent with her approach since her earliest work: she is not a vocalist placed in front of other people's production but a complete musical thinker who happens also to have one of the most distinctive voices working in UK music today. Everything on ZERO begins and ends with her own vision for what the record should be and how it should feel.\n\nThe album title itself carries weight. ZERO is not a statement of absence. It is a statement of origin, of the moment before something becomes defined, the point from which a specific direction is chosen. For an artist who has waited this long and worked this precisely, naming the debut ZERO signals exactly the kind of intentionality that runs through everything she has released.\n\n## The Lineage She Carries\n\n[img:/assets/images/artists/alewya-zero-detail4.jpg]\n\nAlewya has named Grace Jones as a point of reference and aspiration, specifically the quality of uniqueness that makes Jones's work resistant to period dating or genre reduction. The comparison is instructive without being limiting. Both artists share a commitment to physicality in performance, to a relationship between body and sound that cannot be separated. Both carry cultural inheritances that resist easy categorization. But Alewya's work is entirely her own. Her sound is specific to the moment she is operating in, to the West London scenes and East African diasporic communities that shaped her, and to the singular combination of influences she has assembled and tested across more than five years of releases. She is building something that will not sound like anything else, and ZERO is where that project becomes complete.\n\n## What the Album Means in 2026\n\n[img:/assets/images/artists/alewya-zero-detail5.jpg]\n\nZERO arrives at a moment when UK music is producing some of its most interesting and original work in a generation. The conversation about what constitutes British music, about whose experiences and whose influences count as fully British, is being conducted almost entirely by artists like Alewya. Her background refuses any simple national or cultural categorization. Her music carries that refusal as a strength rather than as a complication. ZERO is a debut album in the technical sense only. In every meaningful sense it is the work of an artist who has already done the difficult work of finding out who she is and what she wants to say. What arrives on June 26, 2026 is not an introduction to someone new. It is a long prepared and deeply considered statement from someone who has been waiting to deliver it, and who is fully ready.\n\n[spotify:album/753UpRJw8J0ijOqdPSXwK3]\n\n\nThe debut that arrives ready. ZERO is that record. The conversations it starts are the ones worth having about what British music is becoming.\n\nThe June 2026 release arrives at the right moment. The conversation about who British music belongs to, and whose experiences it represents, is more urgent than it has been in a generation. ZERO participates in that conversation from a position of genuine artistic authority.\n[download:/assets/images/artists/alewya-zero-social-9x16.jpg|Download Social Card]",
