{
  "title": "Crystallmess: Genre Is a Leash She Doesn't Wear",
  "category": "music",
  "author": "Allastair Voss",
  "date": "2026-04-22",
  "image": "/assets/images/artists/crystallmess.jpg",
  "body": "There is a version of club music that is very concerned with being taken seriously, and then there is what Crystallmess does.\n\nBased in Paris and rooted in an Afro-Caribbean heritage that she treats as material rather than backdrop, she builds sets and productions that move between grime, mutant techno, rap instrumentals, and high-speed IDM without pausing to explain any of it. The logic is physical rather than theoretical. You feel it or you don't, and if you don't, you are probably standing in the wrong room.\n\n[spotify:artist/5b4g39OmFtyQcwYLSHCvsC]\n\nChristelle Oyiri grew up in a French Caribbean and African household. Both of those cultural lineages are present in her work, not as decoration or thematic content but as structural forces that shape how she thinks about rhythm, memory, and the relationship between a body and a dancefloor. The distinction matters. A lot of artists from diasporic backgrounds treat that background as a source of aesthetic texture. Oyiri treats it as the actual subject of the inquiry, the thing being turned over and examined and made strange and then made physical again in the space of a set.\n\n## The Sets as Architecture\n\nHer DJ sets are what first built the reputation. Appearances on NTS Radio, a Dazed Mix, performances at Boiler Room, and a Discwoman affiliation that placed her alongside a particular generation of artists treating the dancefloor as a site of serious inquiry. She programmes with speed and intention, moving through tempos and textures in ways that feel curated down to the measure.\n\nThe NTS show, Crystallmess: Unleashed, has been running through 2025 and into 2026, and it functions as the clearest ongoing documentation of how she thinks about selection. Each episode is not a playlist in the usual sense. It is more like an argument, one that builds over the course of an hour through juxtapositions that only make sense after you have already heard them. Zouk does not naturally sit beside Detroit techno. Abrasive zouk at high speed beside afro-trance even less so. But inside her logic the connections are structural, not just tonal. The transitions carry information about where the music comes from and what it shares at the level of rhythm and intention rather than genre taxonomy.\n\nFact Mix 830, released in 2021, is still one of the most instructive documents in her catalogue for understanding the architecture. The Boiler Room appearances demonstrate something different: what it looks like when the architecture meets a live room. She does not perform warmth toward the crowd. She performs commitment to the music, and the crowd responds to that.\n\n## Collective Amnesia and the Politics of the Floor\n\nThe 2018 project Collective Amnesia: In Memory of Logobi is the most explicit statement she has made about why any of this matters beyond aesthetics. Logobi was an Afro-French urban dance form from the mid-2000s, built on a synthesis of hardcore techno and coupé décalé, that thrived in the French African diaspora before being largely forgotten or absorbed into other categories without acknowledgment of where it came from. The project was a multidisciplinary performance combining film and live DJing, and its subject was exactly that forgetting. Post-colonial alienation, technology, DIY culture, the way histories disappear when they belong to people who do not control the archives.\n\nThis is not background context for understanding her music. It is the reason the music has the shape it does. She is not interested in genre as a neutral organisational system. She understands genre as a political technology, a way of sorting music that simultaneously sorts the people who made it. Refusing genre categories is not an aesthetic preference for her. It is a refusal of the sorting mechanism itself.\n\nThe writing confirms this. Her journalism for the Guardian on French colonial revisionism, her contributions to i-D, Noisey, Complex UK, Dazed, and NON Quarterly, these are not side projects. They are the same argument made in a different register. She is as capable of articulating the position verbally as she is of making it felt physically in a room.\n\n## The Production Work\n\nThe production work is where the architecture becomes fully visible. Her club-adjacent tracks are not simply DJ tools. They are fully realised pieces that happen to work in a club context, built with the textural density of IDM and the physical directness of UK club music. She grew up listening to grime, and it shows in the way she approaches rhythm. Not as groove but as pressure. Grime rhythm is confrontational, asymmetric, built to create friction rather than release it. That quality runs through her productions regardless of what other elements are present.\n\nThe SHAPE+ Platform recognition and the Tate Modern Tanks performance locate her in a particular art world context as well as a club context, and this dual location is deliberate. The Tanks at Tate Modern are not a club and they are not a gallery. They are an industrial space that operates in the gap between the two. That gap is exactly where her work lives. The institutional acknowledgment matters less than what it confirms: that the practice is coherent enough, and rigorous enough, to survive translation across very different contexts without losing its character.\n\n## The Couleur Café Set and What It Proves\n\nHer Couleur Café full set in 2025 is the document to start with if you are new to the work. Ninety minutes of pure movement, starting from somewhere almost ambient and arriving at something completely uncompromising, with no obvious transition between the two. That kind of pacing is hard to teach. It comes from having listened to a very large amount of music very carefully, and from having developed a specific understanding of what a crowd is capable of being moved to do if you respect their intelligence rather than managing their expectations.\n\nThe set demonstrates a principle that is easy to state and almost impossible to execute: the dancefloor is not a destination you arrive at. It is a state you build. Most DJs build toward a peak and then sustain or release it. Oyiri builds continuously, so the ninety minutes feel like a single sustained transformation rather than a sequence of moments. The ambient opening is not a warm-up. It is the first argument.\n\n## 2026 and the Expanding Rooms\n\nThe touring schedule in 2026 has expanded significantly. She has played across France, Germany, and the US, and each room has been different in terms of audience expectations and cultural context. She does not adjust to meet those expectations. The rooms adjust.\n\nThis is not stubbornness. It is the natural consequence of having a practice that is too specific to dissolve into general audience-pleasing. The US rooms in particular bring a set of assumptions about what European electronic music means and where it comes from. Those assumptions do not accommodate the actual content of what she makes. She is not a Berlin techno export. She is not a French house act. She is not reducible to any single reference point that an American club audience would arrive with. That gap between expectation and reality is productive. It is where the actual listening happens.\n\nCrystallmess is building something that will look obvious in hindsight. The synthesis of Caribbean and African musical histories with the full range of British and European club traditions, routed through a rigorous intellectual practice and delivered with physical conviction, is not a niche position. It is a description of what global club music actually is if you look at it honestly. Right now it just sounds like the best DJ in the room.\n\n[download:/assets/images/artists/crystallmess-genre-is-a-leash-social-9x16.jpg|Download Social Card]",
  "description": "There is a version of club music that is very concerned with being taken seriously, and then there is what Crystallmess does. Based in Paris and rooted in",
  "image_alt": "Crystallmess: Genre Is a Leash She Doesn't Wear"
}
ENDJSON
echo "Deployed: crystallmess-genre-is-a-leash.json"

